Activity Description

During Global Hack Week: API, the expectation was to build a project that meaningfully used APIs while
demonstrating practical software development skills. For this event, I developed an Android mobile application 
that sends users a daily Bible verse notification at a time they choose. The goal was to create something simple,
useful, and user-focused while integrating backend logic with a clean mobile experience. I successfully built a
working prototype that allows users to set a preferred notification time and receive daily verses, meeting the core
expectations of the event.

Technical Decisions

From a technical perspective, I focused on keeping the architecture simple and reliable. I chose to store Bible verses 
locally in a structured format (such as JSON) to avoid dependency issues with external APIs during development. For 
notifications, I implemented scheduled background tasks to trigger at the user’s selected time. I also designed the app
with a minimal UI to prioritize functionality over complexity, ensuring that the core feature—daily verse delivery—worked
consistently. These decisions helped reduce bugs and allowed me to complete the project within the limited hackathon timeframe.

Contributions

I completed this project independently. I was responsible for all aspects of development, including planning the app concept, 
designing the user interface, implementing the notification system, and testing functionality. Working alone required me to 
manage both technical challenges and time effectively, which helped improve my ability to stay organized and focused under pressure.

Quality Assessment

I would assess my participation as strong and successful. I achieved my main goal of building a fully functional app within the event 
timeframe, and the final product worked as intended. If I were to redo the event, I would focus on expanding the app’s features, such 
as integrating a live Bible verse API, adding user customization options (like verse categories), and improving the UI design for a more 
polished look. Additionally, I would spend more time refining edge cases, such as handling missed notifications or app restarts. Overall,
this experience strengthened my confidence in building complete applications independently and reinforced the importance of balancing 
simplicity with functionality during rapid development.
